\begin{abstract}
This report documents the development of a parking spot detection system using the YOLO11 object detection architecture. The system is designed to identify vehicles and parking enforcement vehicles in street-level imagery obtained from Google Street View. We describe the data collection pipeline, preprocessing steps, and the machine learning workflow employed. The project leverages synthetic data generation via Google's Gemini API to augment the training dataset, addressing the challenge of limited labeled data for parking enforcement vehicles.
\end{abstract}

\tableofcontents
\newpage

%=============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
%=============================================================================

\subsection{Motivation}

Parking enforcement is a critical urban management task that traditionally requires significant human labor. Automating the detection of parking violations---particularly identifying parking enforcement vehicles in restricted zones---presents an opportunity to improve efficiency and consistency in municipal operations.

Computer vision techniques, particularly object detection models, have advanced significantly in recent years. The YOLO (You Only Look Once) family of models offers real-time detection capabilities suitable for deployment in practical applications.

\subsection{Objectives}

The primary objectives of this project are:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Develop a data collection pipeline for acquiring street-level imagery
    \item Implement preprocessing steps to prepare images for machine learning
    \item Train a YOLO11 model to detect two classes: regular vehicles and parking enforcement vehicles
    \item Evaluate model performance and document findings
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Scope}

This project focuses on the Ottawa, Ontario area for data collection. The model is trained to detect:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Class 0: vehicle} --- Regular vehicles (cars, trucks, buses, motorcycles)
    \item \textbf{Class 1: enforcement\_vehicle} --- Parking enforcement vehicles
\end{itemize}

%=============================================================================
\section{Methodology}
%=============================================================================

\subsection{System Architecture}

The project follows a modular pipeline architecture:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Data Collection}: Automated fetching of Google Street View images
    \item \textbf{Preprocessing}: Image cropping and quality filtering
    \item \textbf{Empty Frame Detection}: Identification of frames without vehicles
    \item \textbf{Synthetic Data Generation}: Insertion of vehicles into empty frames
    \item \textbf{Label Generation}: Automated bounding box annotation
    \item \textbf{Dataset Splitting}: Train/validation/test partitioning
    \item \textbf{Model Training}: YOLO11 fine-tuning
    \item \textbf{Evaluation}: Performance metrics and analysis
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Tools and Technologies}

