%=============================================================================
\section{Data Collection}
%=============================================================================

\subsection{Overview}

The data collection phase involved systematically sampling locations within Ottawa and retrieving Google Street View imagery from each location at multiple heading angles.

\subsection{Location Sampling}

\subsubsection{Points Manifest}

A points manifest (\texttt{manifests/points.csv}) was created containing 9,600 entries representing 1,200 unique panorama locations. Each panorama was captured at 8 heading angles (0°, 45°, 90°, 135°, 180°, 225°, 270°, 315°) to provide comprehensive street-level coverage.

The manifest schema includes:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \texttt{street}: Unique identifier for the location
    \item \texttt{label}: Human-readable label combining panorama ID and heading
    \item \texttt{location}: Latitude and longitude coordinates
    \item \texttt{heading}: Compass direction (0--360°)
    \item \texttt{pitch}: Camera tilt angle
    \item \texttt{fov}: Field of view (90°)
    \item \texttt{pano\_id}: Google Street View panorama identifier
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Geographic Coverage}

The sampled locations cover various urban environments in Ottawa, including:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Downtown commercial areas
    \item Residential neighborhoods
    \item Parking lots and street parking zones
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Image Retrieval}

\subsubsection{API Integration}

Images were retrieved using the Google Street View Static API. A custom Python script (\texttt{scripts/02\_fetch\_streetview.py}) was developed to:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Read the points manifest
    \item Construct API requests with appropriate parameters
    \item Download and store images in a structured directory hierarchy
    \item Record metadata in an images manifest (\texttt{manifests/images.csv})
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Directory Structure}

Images were organized by panorama and heading:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
data/images_original/
├── auto_{pano_id}_h0/
│   └── {hash}.jpg
├── auto_{pano_id}_h45/
│   └── {hash}.jpg
└── ...
\end{lstlisting}

Each image filename is a random hash, while the parent directory encodes the panorama ID and heading angle.

\subsubsection{Resume Capability}

The fetch script implements a resume mechanism using the \texttt{--resume} flag. It checks the existing images manifest and only downloads images not already present, enabling recovery from interrupted sessions.

\subsection{Data Quality Assurance}

\subsubsection{Duplicate Detection}

A critical issue emerged during data collection: duplicate images were present in the dataset. Two types of duplicates were identified:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Panorama duplicates}: The same panorama ID appearing multiple times in the manifest
    \item \textbf{File duplicates}: Multiple files in the same directory (same panorama and heading) with identical content
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Panorama-Level Verification}
Using PowerShell and Python scripts, we verified that the points manifest contained exactly 1,200 unique panorama IDs, each with 8 heading entries. No duplicate panoramas were found in the manifest.

\paragraph{File-Level Verification}
The \texttt{jdupes} tool was used to identify byte-identical files. The analysis revealed:
\begin{itemize}
    \item One panorama (\texttt{CcKfN3NH1TTKafS0fsXcjA}) had 2 files in 7 of its 8 heading directories
    \item These duplicates resulted from overlapping data between a previous ZIP archive and the current fetch operation
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Resolution}

Duplicates were removed using:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
jdupes -r -d -N data/images_original
\end{lstlisting}

This command recursively scans, identifies duplicates, preserves the first file in each duplicate set, and deletes the rest without prompting.

\subsubsection{Final Dataset Statistics}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lr}
\toprule
\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Count} \\
\midrule
Unique panoramas & 1,200 \\
Heading angles per panorama & 8 \\
Total images & 9,600 \\
Images manifest entries & 9,600 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Final dataset statistics after cleanup}
\end{table}

%=============================================================================
\section{Image Preprocessing}
%=============================================================================

\subsection{Motivation}

Google Street View images often contain visual elements at the bottom of the frame that are not relevant to parking detection, including:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Copyright watermarks
    \item Timestamp overlays
    \item Navigation UI elements
\end{itemize}

These elements can interfere with model training and should be removed.

\subsection{Implementation}

A cropping script (\texttt{scripts/02b\_crop\_bottom.py}) was developed to remove the bottom 30 pixels from each image.

\subsubsection{Algorithm}

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{Bottom Crop Algorithm}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\For{each row in images manifest}
    \If{status is not ``ok''}
        \State Skip row
    \EndIf
    \If{filename contains ``\_bcN'' suffix}
        \State Skip (already cropped)
    \EndIf
    \If{cropped file exists on disk}
        \State Skip (already cropped)
    \EndIf
    \State Load source image
    \State Crop to $(0, 0, \text{width}, \text{height} - \text{crop\_px})$
    \State Save as \texttt{image\_bc30.jpg}
    \State Update manifest with new file path
\EndFor
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\subsubsection{Idempotency}

The script is designed to be idempotent---running it multiple times produces the same result. It detects already-cropped images through:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Filename suffix matching (\texttt{\_bc30})
    \item Target file existence checking
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{File Preservation}

Original images are preserved on disk. The cropped version is saved as a sibling file with a \texttt{\_bc30} suffix:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
Original: data/images_original/.../abc123.jpg
Cropped:  data/images_original/.../abc123_bc30.jpg
\end{lstlisting}

The manifest \texttt{file\_path} column is updated to reference the cropped version, while \texttt{source\_file\_path} retains the original path.

\subsection{Results}

The cropping operation processed all 9,600 images successfully. Each image now has:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Original file (preserved)
    \item Cropped file (used for training)
\end{itemize}

